e old organizational molds there have been subtle but profound changes to the ways these governing bodies actually work. The authors take as a case study the local government of Zouping County and find that it has been able to evolve significantly through ad hoc bureaucratic adaptations and accommodations that drastically change the operation of government institutions. Zouping has long served as a window into local-level Chinese politics, economy, and culture. In this volume, top scholars analyze the most important changes in the county over the last two decades. The picture that emerges is one of institutional agility and creativity as a new form of resilience within an authoritarian regime.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 4aadministrative financing. 4aauthoritarian resilience. 4abureaucratic adaptation. 4acadre training. 4aeconomic transformation. 4agovernance. 4ainstitutional agility. 4apolitical change. 4apolitical selection. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Economic Policy.2bisacsh1 aGoldstein, Steven, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aOi, Jean C., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311070368940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781503604551zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503604551423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781503604551.jpg  a978-3-11-070368-9  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles